{"title_page": "John Argyris", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = \n| birth_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \u0399\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c7\u03b1\u03c4\u03b6\u03b9 \u0391\u03c1\u03b3\u03cd\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2\n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        =  {{Birth date|df=yes|1913|8|19}} \n| birth_place       =  [[Volos]], Greece\n| death_date        =  {{Death date and age|df=yes|2004|4|2|1913|8|19}}\n| death_place       =  [[Stuttgart]], Germany\n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Imperial College London]]\n* [[University of Stuttgart]]}}\n| patrons           =\n| alma_mater        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[National Technical University of Athens]] \n* [[Technical University Munich]]}}\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = [[Finite element method]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Theodore von Karman Medal]] (1975)\n* [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1986)<ref name=\"frs\"/>}}\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}'''Johann Hadji Argyris''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]<ref name=\"frs\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.2013.0003| title = John Hadji Argyris 19 August 1913 -- 2 April 2004| journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]]| volume = 60| pages = 23| year = 2014| last1 = Spalding | first1 = D. B.| authorlink1 = Brian Spalding}}</ref> ([[Greek alphabet|Greek]]: \u0399\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a7\u03b1\u03c4\u03b6\u03b9 \u0391\u03c1\u03b3\u03cd\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2; 19 August 1913 \u2013 2 April 2004) was a Greek pioneer of computer applications in science and engineering,<ref name=\"nae_2011\">Hughes TJR, [[J. Tinsley Oden|Oden JT]], and Papadrakakis M (2011) ''John H Argyris'', Memorial Tributes: National Academy of Engineering, 15, 24\u201331.</ref> among the creators of the [[finite element method]] (FEM), and lately Professor at the [[University of Stuttgart]] and Director of the Institute for Statics and Dynamics of Aerospace Structures.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/cnm.709| title = Obituary for John Argyris| journal = Communications in Numerical Methods in Engineering| volume = 20| issue = 9| pages = 665| year = 2004| last1 = Doltsinis | first1 = I. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/nme.1131| title = Obituary| journal = International Journal for Numerical Methods in Engineering| volume = 60| issue = 10| pages = 1633| year = 2004| last1 = Doltsinis | first1 = I. }}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus|id= 7102649350}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0045-7825(82)90069-X| title = An excursion into large rotations| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 32| pages = 85| year = 1982| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0045-7825(01)00316-4| title = Computerized integrated approach for design and stress analysis of spiral bevel gears| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 191| issue = 11\u201312| pages = 1057| year = 2002| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. | last2 = Fuentes | first2 = A. | last3 = Litvin | first3 = F. L. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0045-7825(79)90083-5| title = Finite element method \u2013 the natural approach| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 17-18| pages = 1| year = 1979| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. H. | last2 = Balmer | first2 = H.| last3 = Doltsinis | first3 = J. S. | last4 = Dunne | first4 = P. C. | last5 = Haase | first5 = M.| last6 = Kleiber | first6 = M.| last7 = Malejannakis | first7 = G. A. | last8 = Mlejnek | first8 = H. -P. | last9 = M\u00fcller | first9 = M.| last10 = Scharpf | first10 = D. W. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0045-7825(96)01233-9| title = TRIC: A simple but sophisticated 3-node triangular element based on 6 rigid-body and 12 straining modes for fast computational simulations of arbitrary isotropic and laminated composite shells| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 145| pages = 11| year = 1997| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. | last2 = Tenek | first2 = L. | last3 = Olofsson | first3 = L. }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nHe was born in Volos, Greece but the family moved to Athens where he was educated in the Classical Gymnasium.\n\nHe studied civil engineering for four years in the [[National Technical University of Athens]] and then in the [[Technical University Munich]], receiving his Engineering Diploma in 1936.\n\nFollowing his escape from Nazi Germany he completed his Doctorate at [[ETH Zurich]] in 1942<ref>\"John H. Argyris 1913-2004 .\" National Academy of Engineering. 2011. Memorial Tributes: Volume 15. Washington, DC: The National Academies Press. doi: 10.17226/13160\"</ref>.\n\n==Career==\nHis first job was at the Gollnow company in [[Szczecin|Stettin]], where he was involved among other things in high radio transmitter masts. In 1943, he joined the research department of the [[Royal Aeronautical Society]] in England. Starting from 1949 he was lecturer in aeronautical engineering at the [[Imperial College London]] of the [[University of London]], where he assumed a chair in 1955.\n\nIn 1959, Argyris was appointed a professor at the Technical University of Stuttgart (today University of Stuttgart) and director of the Institute for Statics and Dynamics of Aerospace Structures. He created the Aeronautical and Astronautical Campus of the University of Stuttgart as focal point for applications of digital computers and electronics.\n\nArgyris was involved in and developed to a large extent the Finite Element Method along with [[Ray William Clough]] and [[Olgierd Zienkiewicz]] after an early mathematical pre-working of [[Richard Courant]].\n\n==Awards and honours==\nArgyris was awarded the [[Royal Aeronautical Society]] Silver Medal in 1971.<ref>Medallist list published [http://www.aerosociety.com/Assets/Docs/Medals%20and%20Awards/HMA%20-%20List%20of%20RAeS%20Award%20Winners.pdf here].</ref>\n\nHe was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in March 1986.<ref name=\"frs\"/> His nomination reads: {{centred pull quote|Professor Argyris commenced his scientific career at Imperial College in 1949 and subsequently accepted in 1959 a joint appointment as Professor at Imperial College and Professor and Director of the Institute of Astronautical Structures at Stuttgart. Professor Argyris pioneered in the United Kingdom and Europe computer mechanics and established in the early 1950s the matrix structural theory introducing the first finite elements concepts including effects of material and [[geometry|geometrical]] [[Nonlinear system|nonlinearities]].\nThis work initiated an explosive development of [[computational mechanics]] which is still an expanding area. In this field he continued without interruption as one of the leading figures and published a prodigious number of papers (over 300) ranging in applications from structural problems through [[fluid mechanics]], lubrication, [[celestial mechanics]]. The computer system ASKA developed under his direction was the model for many subsequent industrial developments. Professor Argyris has been honoured abroad by a great number of distinctions including the [[Theodore von Karman Medal]], Timoshenko Medal [sic] (ASME), I. B. Laskowitz Gold Medal in Astronautics (N.Y. Acad. Of Sc.) and Copernicus Medal (Polish Acad. Of Sc.).<ref name=\"royal\">{{cite web |url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo==%27EC%2F1986%2F02%27) |title=EC/1986/02: Argyris, John |publisher=The Royal Society |archivedate=30 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Px5P9NWv?url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=%28RefNo%3D%3D%27EC%2F1986%2F02%27%29 |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis uncle, [[Constantin Carath\u00e9odory]], was a [[Greeks|Greek]] mathematician of the [[Modern Era]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlahanas.de/Greeks/new/Argyris.htm|title=John H. Argyris|accessdate=21 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68ZAXdctB?url=http://www.mlahanas.de/Greeks/new/Argyris.htm|archivedate=20 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He died in Stuttgart and is buried in the Sankt J\u00f6rgens Cemetery in the city of Varberg, Sweden.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{FRS 1986}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Argyris, John}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:Structural engineers]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Greek academics|Greek academics]]\n[[Category:People associated with the finite element method]]\n[[Category:Greek engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineering educators]]\n[[Category:Royal Medal winners]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:Technical University of Munich alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Volos]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Royal Aeronautical Society Silver Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = \n| birth_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \u0399\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c7\u03b1\u03c4\u03b6\u03b9 \u0391\u03c1\u03b3\u03cd\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2\n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        =  {{Birth date|df=yes|1913|8|19}} \n| birth_place       =  [[Volos]], Greece\n| death_date        =  {{Death date and age|df=yes|2004|4|2|1913|8|19}}\n| death_place       =  [[Stuttgart]], Germany\n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Imperial College London]]\n* [[University of Stuttgart]]}}\n| patrons           =\n| alma_mater        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[National Technical University of Athens]] \n* [[Technical University Munich]]}}\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = [[Finite element method]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Theodore von Karman Medal]] (1975)\n* [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (1986)<ref name=\"frs\"/>}}\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}'''Johann Hadji Argyris''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]<ref name=\"frs\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.2013.0003| title = John Hadji Argyris 19 August 1913 -- 2 April 2004| journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]]| volume = 60| pages = 23| year = 2014| last1 = Spalding | first1 = D. B.| authorlink1 = Brian Spalding}}</ref> ([[Greek alphabet|Greek]]: \u0399\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a7\u03b1\u03c4\u03b6\u03b9 \u0391\u03c1\u03b3\u03cd\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2; 19 August 1913 \u2013 2 April 2004) was a Greek pioneer of computer applications in science and engineering,<ref name=\"nae_2011\">Hughes TJR, [[J. Tinsley Oden|Oden JT]], and Papadrakakis M (2011) ''John H Argyris'', Memorial Tributes: National Academy of Engineering, 15, 24\u201331.</ref> among the creators of the [[finite element method]] (FEM), and lately Professor at the [[University of Stuttgart]] and Director of the Institute for Statics and Dynamics of Aerospace Structures.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/cnm.709| title = Obituary for John Argyris| journal = Communications in Numerical Methods in Engineering| volume = 20| issue = 9| pages = 665| year = 2004| last1 = Doltsinis | first1 = I. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/nme.1131| title = Obituary| journal = International Journal for Numerical Methods in Engineering| volume = 60| issue = 10| pages = 1633| year = 2004| last1 = Doltsinis | first1 = I. }}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus|id= 7102649350}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0045-7825(82)90069-X| title = An excursion into large rotations| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 32| pages = 85| year = 1982| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0045-7825(01)00316-4| title = Computerized integrated approach for design and stress analysis of spiral bevel gears| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 191| issue = 11\u201312| pages = 1057| year = 2002| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. | last2 = Fuentes | first2 = A. | last3 = Litvin | first3 = F. L. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0045-7825(79)90083-5| title = Finite element method \u2013 the natural approach| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 17-18| pages = 1| year = 1979| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. H. | last2 = Balmer | first2 = H.| last3 = Doltsinis | first3 = J. S. | last4 = Dunne | first4 = P. C. | last5 = Haase | first5 = M.| last6 = Kleiber | first6 = M.| last7 = Malejannakis | first7 = G. A. | last8 = Mlejnek | first8 = H. -P. | last9 = M\u00fcller | first9 = M.| last10 = Scharpf | first10 = D. W. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0045-7825(96)01233-9| title = TRIC: A simple but sophisticated 3-node triangular element based on 6 rigid-body and 12 straining modes for fast computational simulations of arbitrary isotropic and laminated composite shells| journal = Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering| volume = 145| pages = 11| year = 1997| last1 = Argyris | first1 = J. | last2 = Tenek | first2 = L. | last3 = Olofsson | first3 = L. }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nHe was born in Volos, Greece but the family moved to Athens where he was educated in the Classical Gymnasium.\n\nHe studied civil engineering for four years in the [[National Technical University of Athens]] and then in the [[Technical University Munich]], receiving his Engineering Diploma in 1936.\n\n==Career==\nHis first job was at the Gollnow company in [[Szczecin|Stettin]], where he was involved among other things in high radio transmitter masts. In 1943, he joined the research department of the [[Royal Aeronautical Society]] in England. Starting from 1949 he was lecturer in aeronautical engineering at the [[Imperial College London]] of the [[University of London]], where he assumed a chair in 1955.\n\nIn 1959, Argyris was appointed a professor at the Technical University of Stuttgart (today University of Stuttgart) and director of the Institute for Statics and Dynamics of Aerospace Structures. He created the Aeronautical and Astronautical Campus of the University of Stuttgart as focal point for applications of digital computers and electronics.\n\nArgyris was involved in and developed to a large extent the Finite Element Method along with [[Ray William Clough]] and [[Olgierd Zienkiewicz]] after an early mathematical pre-working of [[Richard Courant]].\n\n==Awards and honours==\nArgyris was awarded the [[Royal Aeronautical Society]] Silver Medal in 1971.<ref>Medallist list published [http://www.aerosociety.com/Assets/Docs/Medals%20and%20Awards/HMA%20-%20List%20of%20RAeS%20Award%20Winners.pdf here].</ref>\n\nHe was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in March 1986.<ref name=\"frs\"/> His nomination reads: {{centred pull quote|Professor Argyris commenced his scientific career at Imperial College in 1949 and subsequently accepted in 1959 a joint appointment as Professor at Imperial College and Professor and Director of the Institute of Astronautical Structures at Stuttgart. Professor Argyris pioneered in the United Kingdom and Europe computer mechanics and established in the early 1950s the matrix structural theory introducing the first finite elements concepts including effects of material and [[geometry|geometrical]] [[Nonlinear system|nonlinearities]].\nThis work initiated an explosive development of [[computational mechanics]] which is still an expanding area. In this field he continued without interruption as one of the leading figures and published a prodigious number of papers (over 300) ranging in applications from structural problems through [[fluid mechanics]], lubrication, [[celestial mechanics]]. The computer system ASKA developed under his direction was the model for many subsequent industrial developments. Professor Argyris has been honoured abroad by a great number of distinctions including the [[Theodore von Karman Medal]], Timoshenko Medal [sic] (ASME), I. B. Laskowitz Gold Medal in Astronautics (N.Y. Acad. Of Sc.) and Copernicus Medal (Polish Acad. Of Sc.).<ref name=\"royal\">{{cite web |url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo==%27EC%2F1986%2F02%27) |title=EC/1986/02: Argyris, John |publisher=The Royal Society |archivedate=30 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Px5P9NWv?url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=%28RefNo%3D%3D%27EC%2F1986%2F02%27%29 |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis uncle, [[Constantin Carath\u00e9odory]], was a [[Greeks|Greek]] mathematician of the [[Modern Era]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlahanas.de/Greeks/new/Argyris.htm|title=John H. Argyris|accessdate=21 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68ZAXdctB?url=http://www.mlahanas.de/Greeks/new/Argyris.htm|archivedate=20 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He died in Stuttgart and is buried in the Sankt J\u00f6rgens Cemetery in the city of Varberg, Sweden.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{FRS 1986}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Argyris, John}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:Structural engineers]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Greek academics|Greek academics]]\n[[Category:People associated with the finite element method]]\n[[Category:Greek engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineering educators]]\n[[Category:Royal Medal winners]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:Technical University of Munich alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Volos]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Royal Aeronautical Society Silver Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Pfkilty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Argyris"}
{"title_page": "Karman Thandi", "text_new": "{{short description|Female Indian tennis player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                  = Karman Kaur Thandi\n| image                 = Karman_Kaur_Thandi.jpg\n| caption               = Thandi in Nonthaburi, 2017\n| country               = {{IND}}\n| residence             = [[New Delhi]], India\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1998|06|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place           = New Delhi, India\n| height                = {{convert|1.83|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Karman Kaur Thandi Profile |url=https://www.eurosport.com/tennis/karman-kaur-thandi_prs493900/person.shtml |website=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n| turnedpro             = \n| plays                 = Right (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney      = [[US$]] 82,157\n| singlesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=135|lost=82}}\n| singlestitles         = 0 <br/>1 [[International Tennis Federation|ITF]]\n| highestsinglesranking = {{no wrap|No. 196 (20 August 2018)}}\n| currentsinglesranking = No. 606 (16 March 2020)\n| AustralianOpenresult  = Q1 ([[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|2019]])\n| AustralianOpenjuniorresult = \n| FrenchOpenjuniorresult = 2R ([[2016 French Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2016]])\n| Wimbledonjuniorresult = 2R ([[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|2016]])\n| USOpenjuniorresult    = 3R ([[2015 US Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2015]])\n| doublesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=66|lost=50}}\n| doublestitles         = 0 <br/>4 ITF\n| highestdoublesranking = {{no wrap|No. 186 (31 December 2018)}}\n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesjuniorresult = QF ([[2016 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2016]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesjuniorresult = QF ([[2016 French Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2016]])\n| WimbledonDoublesjuniorresult = 2R ([[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2016]])\n| USOpenDoublesjuniorresult = 1R ([[2015 US Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2015]])\n| Team                  = yes\n| FedCupresult          = {{tennis record|won=5|lost=7}}\n| updated               = 18 March 2019\n}}\n\n'''Karman Kaur Thandi''' (born 16 June 1998) is an [[India]]n [[tennis]] player.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/players/player/323593/title/karman-thandi-0|title=Karman Thandi|last=admin|date=16 July 2018|work=WTA Tennis|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThandi has career-high [[WTA rankings]] of 196 in singles, as of 20 August 2018, and No. 180 in doubles, as of 14 January 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/players/player/323593/title/karman-thandi-0#ranking|title=Karman Thandi|last=admin|date=16 July 2018|work=WTA Tennis|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nShe started playing tennis at the age of eight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100224129|title=Karman Kaur THANDI|website=International Tennis Federation|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThandi is the sixth Indian female tennis player to enter the top 200 of the WTA ranking, after the likes of [[Nirupama Sanjeev]], [[Sania Mirza]], [[Shikha Uberoi]], [[Sunitha Rao]], and [[Ankita Raina]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/karman-kaur-thandi-enters-wta-top-200-only-6th-indian-woman-to-do-so/articleshow/65200986.cms|title=Karman Kaur Thandi enters WTA top-200, only 6th Indian woman to do so - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThandi has won four doubles titles and one singles title on the [[ITF Women's Circuit]]- the maiden singles title in $25,000 Hong Kong tournament on 23 June 2018, and the doubles titles in 2017 in Heraklion, and two in 2015 in Gulbarga. On the junior tour, Thandi had a career-high ranking of No. 32, achieved in January 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100224129|title=Karman Kaur THANDI|website=International Tennis Federation|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> Additionally, she also made it to the semi-finals in two other tournaments in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/sports/report-asian-games-target-is-to-get-medal-for-india-karman-kaur-thandi-2649057|title=Asian Games target is to get medal for India: Karman Kaur Thandi|date=13 August 2018|work=dna|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince 2017 she has represented [[India Fed Cup team|India]] in the [[Fed Cup]], where she has a singles win-loss record of 3\u20136, and a doubles record of 2\u20131<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fedcup.com/en/teams/team.aspx?id=IND|title=Fed Cup - Teams|website=www.fedcup.com|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is backed by the Virat Kohli Foundation<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/winning-hong-kong-event-has-given-me-a-boost-karman-kaur/articleshow/65053593.cms|title=Winning Hong Kong event has given me a boost: Karman Kaur - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> and by [[Mahesh Bhupathi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/karman-kaur-thandi-enters-wta-top-200-only-6th-indian-woman-to-do-so/articleshow/65200986.cms|title=Karman Kaur Thandi enters WTA top-200, only 6th Indian woman to do so - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThandi is participated in the [[2018 Asian Games]], with [[Divij Sharan]] in mixed doubles event. She defeated Filipino pairing of [[Marian Capadocia|Marian Jane Capadocia]] and Alberto Lim jr in their first match in the Games. But the pair was ousted in third round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/sports/report-asian-games-target-is-to-get-medal-for-india-karman-kaur-thandi-2649057|title=Asian Games target is to get medal for India: Karman Kaur Thandi|date=13 August 2018|work=dna|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThandi became the first Indian player to win a WTA main draw match (defeating [[Lu Jia-Jing]] at the [[2018 Jiangxi International Women's Tennis Open]]) since [[Sania Mirza]]'s victory over [[Kristina Barrois]] in the [[2012 BNP Paribas Open]].\n\n==Performance timelines==\n{{Performance key}}\n*Sourced from WTA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/players/323593/karman-thandi/matches|title=Matches|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n===Singles===\n''Only main-draw results in WTA Tour, Grand Slam tournaments, Fed Cup and Olympic Games are included in Win\u2013Loss records.\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n!Tournament\n![[2019 WTA Tour|2019]]\n![[2020 WTA Tour|2020]]\n!SR\n!W\u2013L\n!Win%\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" align=\"left\" |'''Grand Slam tournaments'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Australian Open]]\n|[[2019 Australian Open - Women's Singles Qualifying|Q1]]\n|A\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[French Open]]\n|A\n|\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n|A\n|style=\"color:#ccc;\"|NH\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n|A\n|\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-style=\"background:#efefef; font-weight:bold;\"\n|align=left|Win\u2013Loss\n|0\u20130\n|0\u20130\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" align=\"left\" |'''Premier Mandatory tournaments'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Miami Open (tennis)|Miami Open]]\n|[[2019 Miami Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Q1]]\n|style=\"color:#ccc;\"|P\n|0\u20130\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer