i)\n| {{flagicon|IND}} [[Ankita Raina]]\n| {{flagicon|THA}} [[Nudnida Luangnam]] <br/> {{flagicon|THA}} [[Peangtarn Plipuech]]\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"|W\n| 6\u20134, 6\u20137<sup>(6\u20138)</sup>, 7\u20135\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Fed Cup player}}\n\n{{Top Indian female tennis players}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thandi, Karman Kaur}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2018 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for India]]\n\n\n{{India-tennis-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Female Indian tennis player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                  = Karman Kaur Thandi\n| image                 = Karman_Kaur_Thandi.jpg\n| caption               = Thandi in Nonthaburi, 2017\n| country               = {{IND}}\n| residence             = [[New Delhi]], India\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1998|06|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place           = New Delhi, India\n| height                = {{convert|1.83|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Karman Kaur Thandi Profile |url=https://www.eurosport.com/tennis/karman-kaur-thandi_prs493900/person.shtml |website=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n| turnedpro             = \n| plays                 = Right (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney      = [[US$]] 82,157\n| singlesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=135|lost=82}}\n| singlestitles         = 0 <br/>1 [[International Tennis Federation|ITF]]\n| highestsinglesranking = {{no wrap|No. 196 (20 August 2018)}}\n| currentsinglesranking = No. 606 (16 March 2020)\n| AustralianOpenresult  = Q1 ([[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|2019]])\n| AustralianOpenjuniorresult = \n| FrenchOpenjuniorresult = 2R ([[2016 French Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2016]])\n| Wimbledonjuniorresult = 2R ([[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|2016]])\n| USOpenjuniorresult    = 3R ([[2015 US Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2015]])\n| doublesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=66|lost=50}}\n| doublestitles         = 0 <br/>4 ITF\n| highestdoublesranking = {{no wrap|No. 186 (31 December 2018)}}\n| currentdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesjuniorresult = QF ([[2016 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2016]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesjuniorresult = QF ([[2016 French Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2016]])\n| WimbledonDoublesjuniorresult = 2R ([[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2016]])\n| USOpenDoublesjuniorresult = 1R ([[2015 US Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2015]])\n| Team                  = yes\n| FedCupresult          = {{tennis record|won=5|lost=7}}\n| updated               = 18 March 2019\n}}\n\n'''Karman Kaur Thandi''' (born 16 June 1998) is an [[India]]n [[tennis]] player.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/players/player/323593/title/karman-thandi-0|title=Karman Thandi|last=admin|date=16 July 2018|work=WTA Tennis|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThandi has career-high [[WTA rankings]] of 196 in singles, as of 20 August 2018, and No. 180 in doubles, as of 14 January 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/players/player/323593/title/karman-thandi-0#ranking|title=Karman Thandi|last=admin|date=16 July 2018|work=WTA Tennis|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nShe started playing tennis at the age of eight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100224129|title=Karman Kaur THANDI|website=International Tennis Federation|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThandi is the sixth Indian female tennis player to enter the top 200 of the WTA ranking, after the likes of [[Nirupama Sanjeev]], [[Sania Mirza]], [[Shikha Uberoi]], [[Sunitha Rao]], and [[Ankita Raina]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/karman-kaur-thandi-enters-wta-top-200-only-6th-indian-woman-to-do-so/articleshow/65200986.cms|title=Karman Kaur Thandi enters WTA top-200, only 6th Indian woman to do so - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThandi has won four doubles titles and one singles title on the [[ITF Women's Circuit]]- the maiden singles title in $25,000 Hong Kong tournament on 23 June 2018, and the doubles titles in 2017 in Heraklion, and two in 2015 in Gulbarga. On the junior tour, Thandi had a career-high ranking of No. 32, achieved in January 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100224129|title=Karman Kaur THANDI|website=International Tennis Federation|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> Additionally, she also made it to the semifinals in two other tournaments in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/sports/report-asian-games-target-is-to-get-medal-for-india-karman-kaur-thandi-2649057|title=Asian Games target is to get medal for India: Karman Kaur Thandi|date=13 August 2018|work=dna|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince 2017 she has represented [[India Fed Cup team|India]] in the [[Fed Cup]], where she has a singles win-loss record of 3\u20136, and a doubles record of 2\u20131<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fedcup.com/en/teams/team.aspx?id=IND|title=Fed Cup - Teams|website=www.fedcup.com|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is backed by the Virat Kohli Foundation<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/winning-hong-kong-event-has-given-me-a-boost-karman-kaur/articleshow/65053593.cms|title=Winning Hong Kong event has given me a boost: Karman Kaur - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> and by [[Mahesh Bhupathi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/top-stories/karman-kaur-thandi-enters-wta-top-200-only-6th-indian-woman-to-do-so/articleshow/65200986.cms|title=Karman Kaur Thandi enters WTA top-200, only 6th Indian woman to do so - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThandi is participated in the [[2018 Asian Games]], with [[Divij Sharan]] in mixed doubles event. She defeated Filipino pairing of [[Marian Capadocia|Marian Jane Capadocia]] and Alberto Lim jr in their first match in the Games. But the pair was ousted in third round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/sports/report-asian-games-target-is-to-get-medal-for-india-karman-kaur-thandi-2649057|title=Asian Games target is to get medal for India: Karman Kaur Thandi|date=13 August 2018|work=dna|access-date=25 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThandi became the first Indian player to win a WTA main draw match (defeating [[Lu Jia-Jing]] at the [[2018 Jiangxi International Women's Tennis Open]]) since [[Sania Mirza]]'s victory over [[Kristina Barrois]] in the [[2012 BNP Paribas Open]].\n\n==Performance timelines==\n{{Performance key}}\n*Sourced from WTA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/players/323593/karman-thandi/matches|title=Matches|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n===Singles===\n''Only main-draw results in WTA Tour, Grand Slam tournaments, Fed Cup and Olympic Games are included in Win\u2013Loss records.\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n!Tournament\n![[2019 WTA Tour|2019]]\n![[2020 WTA Tour|2020]]\n!SR\n!W\u2013L\n!Win%\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" align=\"left\" |'''Grand Slam tournaments'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Australian Open]]\n|[[2019 Australian Open - Women's Singles Qualifying|Q1]]\n|A\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[French Open]]\n|A\n|\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n|{{Tennis win percentage|won=0|lost=0|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n|A\n|style=\"color:#ccc;\"|NH\n|0 / 0\n|0\u20130\n